|                       |  FPS | SKIP       |  FPS | SKIP     | FPS  | SKIP      |
|Fullscreen HiColor/YUV | 10,8 | 3380   55% | 15,2 | 2262 37% | 24,0 |    1  0%  |
|Window HiColor         |  9,7 | 3664   60% | 14,3 | 2479 40% | 20,9 |  820 13%  |
|Window TrueColor       |   -  |    -     - |   -  |    -   - | 19,8 | 1104 18%  |
|-----------------------+------+------------+------+----------+------------------+


@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirements"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                               Requirements
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

@{u}Minimum Configuration 68k version:@{uu}

 - An Amiga with AGA (ie. A1200 or A4000) or a graphics card.

 - Kickstart 3.1 or higher (and CyberGraphics/Picasso96 for graphics cards)

 - A 68020 processor (no FPU needed)

 - 1MB of memory.

 - mpega.library installed to enable audio

@{u}Recommended Configuration:@{uu}

 - A graphics card with Picasso96 (and preferably one with PIP hardware)

 - A 68060 processor (you really need this for smooth fullscreen playback)

@{u}Optimal Configuration:@{uu}

 - Vampire Card with Gold2 or newer Core installed

 - Picasso96 with latest saga.card driver and a number of 16 Bit screenmodes 
   (including typical video resolutions like 320x240, 640x480, 800x600 or 
    similar, depending on monitor aspect ratio )

 - mpega.library installed to enable audio (use the faster original mpega 
   instead of the libMAD based one)

 - asyncio.library


@endnode

@node Installation "Installation"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                               Installation
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

RiVA does not need any installation, just copy it to a convenient place on
your harddisk or SSD.

@endnode


@node Transcoding "Transcoding"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                               Transcoding
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

MPEG-1 has never been the most widespread format, as the Video-CD was not too 
successul in a commercial sense. One exception to this observation applies to 
some digital cameras in the mid-2000s which were coding video clips in MPEG-1 
format. 

The bottom line is: Common video material "in the wild" requires transcoding to
be usable with RiVA. This way you can ensure that the video resolution and bit
rate are in ranges that work well with Amiga computers.

For the development of RiVA 0.52, FFMPEG and MEncoder have been used to 
generate the streams.

FFMPEG / MENCODER examples (16:9 aspect ratio):

ffmpeg -i source.mp4 -vcodec mpeg1video -filter:v scale=640:360 -b:v 1500k -bf 3 -ac 2 -acodec mp2 -b:a 128k dest_640x360.mpg

mencoder -of mpeg -mpegopts format=mpeg1:tsaf:muxrate=1500 -o dest_640x360.mpg -aid 1 -vf scale=640:360 -ofps 24 -oac lavc -ovc lavc -lavcopts acodec=mp2:abitrate=128:vcodec=mpeg1video:vbitrate=1500:keyint=15:mbd=2:aspect=16/9:vmax_b_frames=3 source.mp4

Please replace source.mp4 and dest_640x360.mpg with the actual file names.
Both commandlines are supposed to be one-liners. The video bit rate of 
1.5 MBit/s works well with Vampire cards at 78 MHz (x11, Gold2 release).

Something like 192x144 would be a sensible choice for 68k silicon (68060), 
along with bit rates in the 300-500 kBit/s range.

@endnode


@node Usage "Usage"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                   Usage
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

RiVA can be started by one of the following ways:

1. By Double-clicking its icon and selecting a file from the requester
2. By dragging a file on top of RiVA's icon
3. Using the command line (Shell)
4. By using the @{"RivaGUI" link RivaGUI} starter program

To abort playback, press escape or close the window

The Enter key can be used during playback to toggle between fullscreen and
window mode. (only on graphics cards)

The Space can be used to toggle between Halfheight and Normal mode (on AGA only)

For PIP/VLayer playback, the + and - keys on the numeric keypad can be used to
zoom the window. Additionally, you can press keys 1-6 on your keyboard for preset
zoom values (100%, 150%, 200%, 300%, 400% and 500% respectively).


Additionally, RiVA can be configured by the following ways:

1. Adjusting its icon's tooltypes
2. Specifying command-line options


Below is a list of each option with detailed description of what it's for. Please
bear in mind that most options will have an impact on the runtime performance. Windowed
mode is way slower than fullscreen, AHI is way slower than Paula audio. For Vampire
tuning, have a look at DISPLAY, AUDIOQUALITY and AUDIOFREQDIV.

@{u}@{b}OPTIONS:@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}DISPLAY@{uu}

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} DISPLAY=<keyword>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Selects desired display type. This allows you to specify what display format
  RiVA should use for playback. This is useful if the default display RiVA
  selected automatically is not what you want. For instance you may want to use
  a faster HICOLOR mode, instead of the higher quality TRUECOLOR (default).

  Available display types are:

    HICOLOR.........16bit HiColor Screen (Truecolor YUV on Vampire cards, fastest 
                    display option for AMMX version)

    WINDOW..........Normal Window (only on HiColor/TrueColor screens)

    GRAY/GREY.......Standard 8bit grayscale (fastest mode available for 68k)

    TRUECOLOR.......24bit or 32bit TrueColor Screen

    PIP.............Picture-In-Picture (VLayer) Window, not for AMMX

    ACCUPAK.........Special fast YUV Color Mode (available on PicassoIV only)

    DHAM8...........Double-width HAM8 Colour AGA mode (default on AGA)

    DHAM6...........Double-width HAM6 Colour AGA mode (very fast!)

  In Command Line (Shell) mode it is also possible to use 'DISPLAY ?' which brings
  up a display selection menu.

  @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} DISPLAY=HICOLOR

@{u}ZOOM@{uu}

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} ZOOM=<percentage>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  This option lets you specify a default zoom value for PIP (VLayer) playback. The
  value is a percentage.

  @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} ZOOM=200

@{u}FPS@{uu}

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} FPS=<value>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Allows framerate to be specified. This lets you control playback speed.
  It's useful since some MPEGs have been encoded with the wrong framerate, this
  lets you specify the correct framerate for those files.

  It's also useful in combination with the NOSKIP and VERBOSE options to test the
  maximum speed your machine can play a particular MPEG with the given DISPLAY mode.
  (ie FPS 1000 NOSKIP VERBOSE as command line arguments give you the maximum speed)

  @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} FPS=15

@{u}NOSKIP@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Disables frame-skipping. With this option, RiVA will not attempt to keep
  up with the specified framerate by skipping frames.

  This option is not recommended with files containing audio, because framerate may
  not be maintained correctly, causing audio 'gaps'.

@{u}HALFHEIGHT@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Displays MPEG with halved vertical resolution. This mode will only work in AGA
  modes and achieves great speedup in colour! Also requires Kickstart 3.1+ !
  Will only work in PAL!

@{u}PICASSO96@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub} Forces RiVA to use Picasso96 graphics system.

@{u}BORDERLESS@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub} Forces RiVA to open playing window without GUI borders.

@{u}CYBERGFX@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub} Forces RiVA to use CyberGfx system.

@{u}AGA@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub} Use PAL screen on AGA.

@{u}FULLPIP@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Displays MPEGs in a fullscreen borderless PIP window. The Enter key can be
  used to toggle between fullscreen mode and normal mode during playback.


@{u}PIVPLANARASSIST@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Uses the special PlanarAssist hardware of the PicassoIV.

  This option is not available with the current Picasso96 v2.0 release. It
  requires a special PicassoIV.card, which has never been officially released
  by the Picasso96 team.

  When this is enabled, PIP playback will be considerably faster.

@{u}AHI@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Forces RiVA to output audio via AHI. If audio.device cannot be opened (e.g.
  on non-classic Amigas), RiVA shall try to use AHI by default. On classic
  Amiga systems RiVA will use the standard audio.device, unless this option
  is specified. Please note that AHI is not well runtime optimized. Enabling 
  AHI will reduce the overall playback speed.

@{u}HQAUDIO@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  This option will enable 14 Bit audio output over Paula. The corresponding
  code is quite runtime optimized and will perform better than AHI.
  
  Please note that this option also enables true 16 Bit audio output on 
  Vampire V4.

@{u}NOAUDIO@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Disables audio playback. If no audio output is required, this option will
  greatly speed up playback.

@{u}NOVIDEO@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Disables video decoding. Can be useful if only audio playback is desired.

@{u}NORENDER@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Disables video display. Video is decoded, but not displayed. Useful for testing
  how much your video bandwith is limiting playback speed. (you can compare
  speed test with and without this option to see if it's worth upgrading to a
  GfxCard with faster memory bus :))

@{u}NOP@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Forces P frames to be skipped. (Useful for performance calculations)

@{u}NOB@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Forces B frames to be skipped. (Useful for performance calculations)

@{u}PUBSCREEN@{uu}

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} PUBSCREEN=<public screen name>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  This option lets you specify a public screen on which the RiVA window is to be
  opened. (By default the window is opened on the Workbench screen)

  @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} PUBSCREEN=MyPublicScreen

@{u}MONOSURROUND@{uu}

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Enables an experimental surround audio effect. This option should make audio to
  be more enjoyable compared to a flat mono sound. May increase synchronisation
  problems though.  

@{u}AUDIOQUALITY@{uu}

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} AUDIOQUALITY=<value>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Lets you specify the quality of audio decoding. The quality options are the same
  as in mpega:

  AUDIOQUALITY=0....Worst Quality
  AUDIOQUALITY=1....Medium Quality
  AUDIOQUALITY=2....High Quality

  Default is 1 (Medium Quality).

  If illegal values are encountered, the default setting will be used.

@{u}AUDIOFREQDIV@{uu}

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} AUDIOFREQDIV=<value>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Frequency division to be used for audio decoding. Values are the same as in mpega:

  AUDIOFREQDIV=1....Use Full Frequency (ie. 32 kHz, 44.1 kHz, 48 kHz...)
  AUDIOFREQDIV=2....Use Half Frequency (ie. 16 kHz, 22 kHz, 24 kHz...)
  AUDIOFREQDIV=4....Use Quarter Frequency (ie. 8 kHz, 11 kHz, 12 kHz...)

  Higher frequency means more CPU time used, resulting in slower video updates.

  Default is 2 (Half Frequency).

  For illegal values given, the default setting will be used.

  The AMMX version of RiVA will check whether ECS is available and
  also whether the Amiga Chipset is likely in double scan mode (P96
  environment variable ENV:Picasso96/AmigaVideo ). If that is the
  case, the default will be 1 for no frequency division. Bear in
  mind that AUDIOFREQDIV=1 won't work on OCS Amigas when the sampling
  rate is >28 kHz.

@{u}SAVEAUDIO@{uu}

  [command-line only]

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} SAVEAUDIO=<audio filename>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  This option lets you save the audio from MPEG files with audio.

  The audio will be constantly saved into the file during playback until the end
  of the MPEG file is reached or the user aborts playback.

  IMPORTANT: Make sure you have enough free space for the audio to be saved!

  @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} SAVEAUDIO=RAM:MyAudioFile.mp2

@{u}DEFAULTDIR@{uu}

  @{b}USAGE:@{ub} DEFAULTDIR=<path for default directory>

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  The default directory used in the filerequester can be specified with this option.

  @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} DEFAULTDIR="Work:MyMovies/MPEGs"

@{u}VGA or MULTISCAN@{uu}

  [command-line only]

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Use Multiscan Productivity screen on AGA. Currently only available as command
  line argument and not yet implemented in colour modes (in colour it'd be much
  slower due to increased AGA bandwidth usage and HALFHEIGHT option is not
  possible). Best to use a scandoubler, but I can implement this if requested.

@{u}RTG or AKIKO@{uu}

  [command-line only]

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Use OS RTG rendering routines. This should also automatically use the AKIKO C2P
  hardware of a CD32 if available.

@{u}VERBOSE@{uu}

  [command-line only]

  @{b}DESCRIPTION:@{ub}

  Displays some information about the MPEG being played and gives some statistical
  feedback (ie. playback speed etc.)

@endnode



@node RivaGUI "RivaGUI"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                 RivaGUI
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}


RivaGUI is a simple MUI-based starter application, designed to make using RiVA
more convenient.

With this program you can select an MPEG file for playing, set a number of
options for playback (video and audio options) and RiVA will be invoked with
the appropriate command line options, when the Play button is pressed.

You can also specify the RiVA Executable file, which you want RivaGUI to use for
playback.

The 'Save Prefs' button saves the settings in a prefs file, including the path
of the directory in which the last MPEG file was selected.

The 'Load Prefs' button loads the last saved settings.

RivaGUI was written by Gábor Nagy.

RivaGUI may be used with the AMMX version as well. The commandline options
were kept compatible. Please refer to the @{"Usage" link Usage} section
for information how the RivaGUI settings map on the commandline and
tooltypes.

@endnode




@node Reg "Registration"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                               Registration
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}


When you register RiVA, you will receive the full version which has colour
playback as well.

By registering you also support the development of RiVA and other future
Amiga projects.

The quickest and easiest way to register is via RegNet. To register online, go
to the following webpage:

  https://secure.reg.net/Product.asp?ID=9546

Using RegNet, you will normally receive your registration within 48 hours.

Please use the online registartion if possible, because registration via
snail-mail is not only slower, but is also more risky (the postman could
get rich...)

If there's no way you can register online, you can register by sending the
registration fee along with a registration form in an envelope via conventional
mail to the following address:

         Istvan Fellner
         1139 Budapest
         Szegedi ut 5. II/22.
         HUNGARY

Here is a list of currencies and the amount required as the registration fee
that will be accepted:

  10 UKP  (UK Pounds)
  15 USD  (US Dollars)
  15 EURO (Adopted currency in the European Union)

Only cash is accepted, no foreign cheques, bank transfers or money orders...

DO NOT USE COINS! Only use bank notes and always put the money between a few
pages of paper so that it is not obvious that there is money in there,
otherwise the mailman could get rich, and I may never get your registration. :(

After your registration was received, the full version will be sent to you
in the form you have specified in your registration form. Typical delivery
time using conventional snail mail is between 1 and 2 weeks. When using
email, the program should be sent to you on the same day of receiving the
registration fee.

Please take your time to fill in all the information on the registration form.

With your registration you support my program and encourage me to continue
development of RiVA and other great programs for the Amiga.

Thank you for supporting the Amiga and the concept of shareware!

@endnode

@node Bugs "Current Bugs"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                               Current Bugs
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

If you find any bugs, crashes or unpredictable behaviour of this program,
please do not hesistate to contact the @{"author" link Contact}.

If you contact me with a bugreport, please give me a detailed description of
your system configuration (both software and hardware) and describe exactly how
the crash happened, so I can try to reproduce the bug with a similar configuration
under the same situation.

@endnode

@node History "History"
@{b}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                 History
---------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

